claim:
There were significant gains in students’ average self-efficacy ratings (matched-pairs Wilcoxon signed rank test, P < 0.0001) and science identity ratings (matched-pairs Wilcoxon signed rank test, P = 0.004), but not in the science community values ratings (matched-pairs Wilcoxon signed rank test, P = 0.605) (Appendix 6).Factors influencing change in skills and attitudes
Normalized change in skills was lowest for the students with the highest presemester skills scores (quartile 4); however, normalized change in skills did not significantly vary across the four quartiles of presemester scores (Welch’s analysis of variance [ANOVA], P = 0.134) (Fig. 3A).
